-- Japan, China and Thailand: Asian Local Bonds and Foreign Exchange Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-11-16T23:21:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-16/japan-china-and-thailand-asian-local-bonds-and-foreign-exchange-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Markets in India, Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore are
closed for a public holiday.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Cabinet Office will release its final report on leading
and coincident indexes for September at 2 p.m. in Tokyo. The
leading index, a composite of 12 indicators including
inventories and machine orders, fell to 98.9 from 99.5 in August,
according to a preliminary estimate on Nov.8. The coincident
index, a composite of 11 indicators including factory production
and retail sales, fell to 102.0 from 103.3, the estimate showed.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was 1.025 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.34 per dollar at 8:19 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: China will sell 28 billion yuan ($4.22 billion) of
50-year bonds. The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015
was 3.11 percent. The yuan was at 6.6441 per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will sell 10 billion baht
($334 million) of bonds due 2021. The yield on the 5.85 percent
note due March 2021 was 3.72 percent. The baht traded at 29.88
per dollar.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at 
 fyoon2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
